default3. default              defaultThe defaultimpact of welfare reform on our communitiesdefault3.1
default              
defaultIt is clear from the feedback we 
defaulthave received that 
defaultthe impact of welfare reform will be
default variable around the country. This is not a surprise to us and reflects the diversity 
defaultof communities, local economies
default and housing markets. W
defaulthilst we understand that the government will seek 
defaultcomposite headline facts and figures we expect that such data 
defaultmay 
defaultmask the reality of this diversity and would urge continuing attention to the impact at a regional level. 
default3.2
default              
defaultA case in point here is the 
default“spare room subsidy” or
default “bedroom tax”. Whilst all HAs report likely adverse impacts on their communities of the refor
defaultms as a whol
defaulte, the bedroom tax is of huge
default concern to those in the Midlands, the North and in some rural communities where much of the housing stock comprises larger properties and flexible allocation policies have been promoted by partner LAs. Planned unde
defaultr-occupation has facilitated long-term residence as families grow as well as securing acceptance of low demand stock –e.g. in high rise blocks – thus reducing v
defaultoid costs. 
default3.3
default              
defaultThe proportion of 
defaultour members’ 
defaulttenants affected by the bedroom tax ranges from 
default5
default-20%, the higher levels being in the North where many HAs have several thousand under-occupying households. They will not be able to move tenants who want to downsize due to the scarcity of smaller properties and there is the potential for an oversupply of
default 3Bed + vacancies (with a cons
defaultequent impact on void
default costs) if new applicants with a strict 2bed need are unable to accept larger properties for financial reasons. This in turn will increase waiting times for smaller properties with an impact on temporary h
defaultousing costs.
default And where tenants are able to move they may have to move far away from their friends, family and 
defaultsupport networks and also from the schools which their children attend causing great upheaval and isolation.
default3.4
default              
defaultAn e
defaultxample here is a Midlands 
defaultho
defaultusing group with over 600 tenants affected by the bedroom tax and mainly “under-occupying” 
default3 bedroom properties. 
defaultThis HA does not have 
defaultlarge families in overcrowded conditions 
defaultwaiting for 3 bedroom homes and such
default properties have now become much harder to
default l
defaultet because the demand in the area
default is now 
defaultlargely for 2 bedroom homes. An analysis of 3-bedroom 
defaultlettings in July 2013 showed that all were let to those with low needs and in some cases it took more than one bidding cycle to allocate any household to these properties at all. 
default3.5
default              
defaultWhilst changes to specific benefits are of concern, our members are equa
defaultlly worried about the cumulative ef
defaultfect of
default 
defaultreforms on their residents
default an
defaultd the blanket application of
default changes across the country
default. Many 
defaultreforms will happen consecutively with the impact of the bedroom tax, benefits cap and consolidated single UC payment hitt
defaulting people at the same time as they are, for example, 
defaultalso possibly required to pay 
defaultcontribution
defaults
default towards council tax or face losing disability payments. This combination of event
defaults in addition to the 
default1% cap on future benefit uplifts will create significant
default fina
defaultncial pressures on communities. 
defaultGrowing homelessness as debt related evictions increase with visible signs of acute poverty are inevitable.
