default6.2.2
default              
defaultThe concerns around housing costs being included in Universal Credit payments 
defaultrather than being paid directly to landlords 
defaultare well documented. 
defaultWe are particularly worried that under UC job seekers 
defaultwho are subject to sanction will lose all their benefits and risk losing their home 
defaulttoo 
defaultwhereas those being sanctioned currently do not lose Housing Benefit.
default We are also concerned that “vulnerable” people who are not living in specialist accommodation will
default be expected to self-determine their vulnerability in order to have their housing costs paid direct to landlords, a requirement that
default is unlikely to protect 
defaultthose most in need of support.
default6.2.3
default              
defaultIncreased operational costs as HAs take on additional staff (or
default partner with other agencies to do so) to try to mitigate the impact – e.g. welfare advisers, income collection staff and digital inclusion support staff.
default6.2.4
default              
defaultIncreased transactional costs for rent collection as a result of UC being paid in one sum direc
defaultt to tenants. Estimates for the increased cost of collecting payments from every individual tenant in receipt of benefit (rather than receiving bulk payments from LAs) range from £50k-£350k per HA.
default6.2.5
default              
defaultIncreased legal fees for enforcement action with som
defaulte uncertainty as to how courts will cope with and respond to increased repossession claims.
default6.2.6
default              
defaultIncreased void turnaround costs due to difficulty in letting unaffordable larger units, increased evictions and many LAs passing on council tax benefit cuts b
defaulty removing relief on void properties (the impact of which alone was est
defaultimated as £100k pa by one member
default). 
